<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-03-24T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-03-24T02:00:00-05:00" n="775" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d775">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">698.002/1007: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Butrick</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-03-24T15:00:00+08:00">March 24, 1940—3
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 28—1:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>245. Chungking’s 134, March 19, 10 a.m., and previous. Inspector
                                General in letter dated yesterday informed me that he has been
                                authorized by telegram from Minister of Finance at Chungking to act
                                at his discretion in regard to resumption of customs activities at
                                Nanking and Chinkiang when the Yangtze is reopened to foreign
                                trade.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Peiping and Chungking. Code text by air mail to
                                Tokyo.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Butrick</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>